The paper deals with community detection in networks, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of stochastic block models and their variants suggests that the paper could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.LG (Machine Learning). The focus on degree distributions and heavy-tailed distributions suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) or cs.SD (Systems and Control). Finally, the use of directed graphs and edge orientations suggests that the paper could belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI and cs.LG, followed by cs.DM, cs.SD, and cs.NE.
